('reading', NULL, 111, 'Passage 12:\n\nAncient Rome was one of the most influential civilizations in history, lasting for over a thousand years from its legendary founding in 753 BCE until the fall of the Western Roman Empire in 476 CE. Rome began as a small city-state in central Italy but eventually grew to control a vast empire that stretched from Britain to North Africa and from Spain to the Middle East.\n\nThe Roman Republic, established around 509 BCE, introduced political innovations that influenced later democratic systems. The Republic was governed by elected officials, including consuls and senators, though power was largely held by wealthy patrician families. Over time, conflicts between patricians and plebeians (common citizens) led to reforms that gave plebeians more political rights.\n\nRoman engineering and architecture were remarkably advanced. The Romans built an extensive network of roads that facilitated trade and military movement throughout the empire. They also constructed aqueducts to transport water to cities, some of which are still standing today. Roman architectural innovations, such as the arch and concrete, enabled the construction of massive structures like the Colosseum and the Pantheon.\n\nRoman culture had a lasting impact on Western civilization. Latin, the language of Rome, became the basis for the Romance languages, including Italian, French, Spanish, and Portuguese. Roman law, particularly the concept of legal rights and citizenship, influenced modern legal systems. Even after its fall, Rome''s legacy continued through the Byzantine Empire and profoundly shaped European culture and thought.\n\nWhat is the main topic of the passage?', 'The fall of the Roman Empire', 'The innovations and lasting influence of ancient Rome', 'Roman military conquests', 'The Latin language', 'b'),
