-- PASSAGE 13: Sleep and Health (Questions 121-130)
('reading', NULL, 121, 'Passage 13:\n\nSleep is a fundamental biological need that plays a crucial role in maintaining physical and mental health. During sleep, the body undergoes numerous restorative processes, including tissue repair, muscle growth, and the consolidation of memories. Despite its importance, many people fail to get adequate sleep due to busy schedules, stress, or sleep disorders.\n\nThe recommended amount of sleep varies by age, but most adults need between seven and nine hours per night. Sleep occurs in cycles, each lasting approximately 90 minutes and consisting of different stages. These stages include light sleep, deep sleep, and REM (Rapid Eye Movement) sleep. Each stage serves distinct functions: deep sleep is particularly important for physical restoration, while REM sleep is crucial for cognitive functions such as learning and memory.\n\nChronic sleep deprivation has serious health consequences. Studies have linked insufficient sleep to increased risks of obesity, diabetes, cardiovascular disease, and weakened immune function. Sleep deprivation also impairs cognitive performance, affecting attention, decision-making, and reaction time. This is particularly dangerous for activities requiring alertness, such as driving.\n\nImproving sleep quality involves practicing good "sleep hygiene." This includes maintaining a consistent sleep schedule, creating a comfortable sleep environment, avoiding caffeine and electronic devices before bedtime, and engaging in regular physical activity. For those with persistent sleep problems, consulting a healthcare provider is advisable.\n\nWhat is the main purpose of the passage?', 'To describe the stages of sleep', 'To explain the importance of sleep and ways to improve it', 'To discuss sleep disorders', 'To argue against working long hours', 'b'),
