('reading', NULL, 141, 'Passage 15:\n\nBiodiversity refers to the variety of life on Earth, encompassing the diversity of species, genetic variation within species, and the variety of ecosystems. High biodiversity is essential for the stability and resilience of ecosystems, as diverse systems are better able to withstand environmental changes and disturbances. Unfortunately, biodiversity is declining at an alarming rate due to human activities.\n\nHabitat destruction is the leading cause of biodiversity loss. As forests are cleared for agriculture, urban development, and logging, countless species lose their homes and food sources. Tropical rainforests, which contain more than half of the world''s species despite covering only about 7% of Earth''s land surface, are particularly vulnerable. Deforestation in these regions has severe consequences for global biodiversity.\n\nOther threats to biodiversity include pollution, climate change, overexploitation of resources, and the introduction of invasive species. Invasive species can outcompete native species for resources, disrupt food chains, and alter habitats. Climate change is forcing species to adapt to new conditions or migrate to more suitable environments, but many species cannot adapt quickly enough or have nowhere to go.\n\nConserving biodiversity requires coordinated efforts at local, national, and international levels. Strategies include establishing protected areas such as national parks and wildlife reserves, enforcing laws against poaching and illegal logging, restoring degraded habitats, and promoting sustainable resource use. Additionally, raising public awareness about the importance of biodiversity is crucial for long-term conservation success.\n\nWhat is the main topic of the passage?', 'The definition of biodiversity', 'The importance of biodiversity, threats to it, and conservation strategies', 'The benefits of deforestation', 'Specific endangered species', 'b'),
