('reading', NULL, 191, 'Passage 20:\n\nUrbanization is the process by which an increasing percentage of a population comes to live in cities and urban areas. This phenomenon has accelerated dramatically over the past century. In 1900, only about 13% of the world''s population lived in urban areas; by 2020, this figure had risen to over 56%, and it continues to grow. This rapid urbanization has profound implications for economies, societies, and the environment.\n\nEconomically, cities serve as engines of growth and innovation. They concentrate resources, infrastructure, and human capital, creating opportunities for businesses and workers. Urban areas typically offer higher wages, better access to education and healthcare, and more diverse employment opportunities than rural areas. This economic advantage is a primary driver of rural-to-urban migration.\n\nHowever, rapid urbanization also presents significant challenges. Many cities struggle to provide adequate housing, infrastructure, and services for their growing populations. This can lead to the development of informal settlements or slums, where residents lack access to basic amenities such as clean water, sanitation, and electricity. Traffic congestion, air pollution, and strain on public services are common problems in rapidly growing cities.\n\nEnvironmentally, urbanization has both positive and negative effects. Dense cities can be more energy-efficient than sprawling suburban development, as they enable the use of public transportation and reduce the need for private vehicles. However, urban areas also contribute significantly to greenhouse gas emissions, generate large amounts of waste, and can disrupt local ecosystems. Sustainable urban planning, which emphasizes green spaces, efficient public transportation, and environmentally friendly building practices, is essential for creating livable cities in the future.\n\nWhat is the main topic of the passage?', 'The history of cities', 'The process, impacts, an